6":"about 1246","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Bletsoe, Bedfordshire, England":"Bletsoe, Bedfordshire, England","Stonegrave, Yorkshire, England":"Stonegrave, Yorkshire, England","Nunnington, Helmsley, Yorkshire, England":"Nunnington, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":13,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":44,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Steyngreve was born about 1246, in Stonegrave, Yorkshire, England, his father, Simon Stonegrave, was 43 and his mother, Beatrice Foliot, was 34. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Ida Wake. He died in 1295, at the age of 50."},"et":{"about 1246–1295":"umbes 1246–1295","1239–1263":"1239–1263","1246–1295":"1246–1295","1255–1295":"1255–1295","1271–1324":"1271–1324","–1295":"–1295","1205–1257":"1205–1257","1214–Female":"1214–Surnud","Aft 1257":"pärast 1257","1263":"1263","1295":"1295","1271":"1271","1290":"1290","1239":"1239","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","Abt 1271":"umbes 1271","1214":"1214","1324":"1324","1257":"1257","1246":"1246","1255":"1255","about 1246":"umbes 1246","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Bletsoe, Bedfordshire, England":"Bletsoe, Bedfordshire, England","Stonegrave, Yorkshire, England":"Stonegrav